        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I agree! I have no idea what the market will do next year, but I don\xe2\x80\x99t think this is a bubble (outside of a few names). I\xe2\x80\x99m willing to bet that over the next five to ten years, owning today\xe2\x80\x99s leading tech companies and investing in the next generation will outperform cash or indices.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         To be bearish would be to underestimate exponential acceleration. The \xe2\x80\x9cCOVID accelerated x trend by 5-10 years\xe2\x80\x9d thing that everyone says is too static. It undersells what five to ten years mean these days.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         If you believe Ray Kurzweil (do people still believe Kurzweil?) or ARK Invest\xe2\x80\x99s Cathie Wood (hard to argue with Cathie Wood), technology improves at accelerating rates. By pulling certain trends like eCommerce, remote work, online education, and crypto forward by 5-10 years, COVID actually accelerated growth and productivity exponentially, and set a new, higher base off of which even faster-accelerating technology will be built.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         ARK\xe2\x80\x99s theses are largely based on Wright\xe2\x80\x99s law, which states that costs decline as more units are produced, which generates more demand, driving costs down further. It\xe2\x80\x99s exponential improvement.
        </p>
